  <h2>Surgical Services We Offer</h2>
  <p>
    All About Pets performs a range of surgical procedures in our well-equipped facility. Our team follows strict protocols for anesthesia, sterility, and patient monitoring to ensure the safest possible experience for every surgical patient.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spay (ovariohysterectomy)</strong> — removes the ovaries and uterus in female pets, preventing reproduction and reducing the risk of certain cancers and infections</li>
    <li><strong>Neuter (castration)</strong> — removes the testes in male pets, reducing roaming, aggression, and the risk of testicular cancer and prostate disease</li>
    <li><strong>Soft tissue surgery</strong> — procedures involving skin, organs, and body cavities, including lump removals, bladder surgery, and intestinal procedures</li>
    <li><strong>Dental extractions</strong> — removal of fractured, infected, or mobile teeth that cause pain or risk spreading oral infection</li>
    <li><strong>Laceration repair</strong> — closure of wounds that require surgical debridement and suturing</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Pre-Operative Care</h2>
  <p>
    Before any elective or non-emergency procedure, we conduct a thorough pre-surgical assessment. This typically includes a physical examination and may include bloodwork to evaluate organ function and anesthesia risk. We'll discuss what to expect, provide fasting instructions, and answer all your questions before the day of surgery.
  </p>

  <h2>Anesthesia and Monitoring</h2>
  <p>
    Your pet's safety under anesthesia is our highest priority. We use modern, safe anesthetic protocols tailored to your pet's species, age, weight, and health status. Throughout every procedure, a dedicated team member monitors vital signs — heart rate, respiratory rate, temperature, and oxygen saturation — continuously.
  </p>

  <h2>Post-Operative Care</h2>
  <p>
    After surgery, your pet recovers in a warm, quiet space with close monitoring until they are stable and alert. Before you take them home, we review all discharge instructions in detail — including activity restrictions, incision care, signs to watch for, and pain medication administration. We're always available for follow-up questions.
  </p>
  <p>
    A post-surgical recheck is typically scheduled 10–14 days after the procedure to assess healing and remove sutures if needed.
  </p>

